			<p>One of the most common questions we get from couples planning <a href="/weddings">South Asian weddings in Vancouver</a> — and from corporate event planners — is some version of: "Is your food halal?" The answer matters more than a simple yes or no. Halal certification involves the entire chain from farm to plate, and getting it right is essential when you're catering for guests who observe Islamic dietary law.</p>

			<h2>What <em>Halal</em> Actually Means</h2>
			<p>Halal is an Arabic word meaning "permissible" — referring to food prepared according to Islamic law. For meat to be considered halal, several conditions must be met: the animal must be healthy at the time of slaughter, the slaughter must be performed by a Muslim, the animal's blood must be fully drained, and a specific blessing must be invoked.</p>
			<p>Pork and pork-derived products (including gelatin and many flavour additives) are not halal. Alcohol used in cooking is also not halal — important to note for dishes that might use cooking wine or vanilla extract.</p>

			<h2>Halal-Certified vs. Halal-Friendly</h2>
			<p>There's a meaningful difference between "halal-certified" and "halal-friendly." Certified means the meat has been verified by an independent halal certification body. Friendly often just means the kitchen avoids pork — but the meat itself may not be from a certified halal supplier.</p>
			<p>For weddings and corporate events where guests strictly observe halal, you want certified meat, full stop.</p>

			<h2>Questions to Ask <em>Any Caterer</em></h2>
			<p>Before booking, ask these specific questions:</p>
			<ul>
				<li>Are your chicken and lamb halal-certified, and which certification body verifies your supplier?</li>
				<li>Do you use any pork or pork-derived ingredients in any dish (including stocks, sausages, or flavourings)?</li>
				<li>Do you cook with alcohol in any sauces or marinades?</li>
				<li>Are halal dishes prepared on separate equipment from non-halal items?</li>
				<li>Can you provide documentation on request?</li>
			</ul>
			<p>A reputable caterer should answer all of these without hesitation. If they're vague, ask follow-ups.</p>

			<h2>Why It Matters at <em>Multi-Cultural Events</em></h2>
			<p>Vancouver weddings often bring together families from different religious traditions. Hindu and Sikh side, Muslim side, vegetarian elders, vegan friends. The bar isn't just "is the food halal?" — it's "can every guest at this wedding eat with confidence?"</p>
			<p>That's why we maintain dedicated kitchen areas for vegetarian and Jain dishes alongside our halal-certified meat preparation. It's not enough to offer the right options. They need to be prepared in a way that honours the trust each guest is placing in your hospitality.</p>

			<h2>Corporate Catering and <em>Halal</em></h2>
			<p>For Vancouver offices, halal is increasingly part of standard <a href="/blog/office-catering-vancouver-large-groups">corporate catering planning</a>. Even if you don't have a single colleague who explicitly asks for halal, including halal-certified options is the simplest way to ensure everyone at the table can eat. It's also the easiest way to avoid uncomfortable conversations on the day of an event.</p>

			<h2>What Sula Does</h2>
			<p>All chicken and lamb served at Sula — across our restaurants and our catering — is halal-certified through trusted local BC suppliers. We can provide documentation on request. Our pure-vegetarian and Jain dishes are prepared in dedicated areas. And we never use pork or alcohol in any dish.</p>
			<p>If you're planning a multi-cultural event and want to make sure every guest is honoured, <a href="https://sulaindianrestaurant.com/request-a-quote/">request a quote</a> and we'll walk you through every detail.</p>

